>Get lost on a hike. No idea where you are.
>Stumble on a surprised fox, one holding a basket and a fishing rod in her paw-like hands.
>Realize you're REALLY lost.
>Properly meet Francine Fox of Pinewood Village.
>Hit it off immediately, and she leads you back to town.
>She introduces you to some of her friends and neighbors, like Walter Wolf, Marci Mare, Tina Tabby, and a few others who welcome you as well.
>You're sensing a theme here.
>Francine offers you her guest bedroom as long as you need, and says not to worry about paying her back.
>Her house is small, but it's far better than fending for yourself as you get your bearings. You accept, much to her delight.
>Help Francine out with her chores and daily stuff as you try to figure out where you are.
>After the excitement dies down, things settle into a routine.
>Pinewood seems to be slowly moving forward at it's own pace, not caring about the outside world. The village is disconnected, but peaceful. No internet, no cellphones, nothing of the sort.
>This gives you time to learn how things are done here. Francine gladly tutors you on small town living, teaching you all about gardening, crafting, cooking (though she likes to do that one for you both) and countless other things.
>Its a lot to absorb, but your vulpine friend never mocks your failures, no matter how much she loves teasing you over other things
>Days turn to weeks, and weeks turn to months, and you wonder where your plans to leave went. The thought of leaving Pinewood isn't fun, but the thought of leaving Francine outright hurts.
>She's special to you.
>Then Francine surprises you
>She approaches you, a blush on her white, furry cheeks, then she asks. "Anon? We're close friends you and I, close as can be, but I... Wish to be more. You're handsome, kind, and patient with fox antics that others roll their eyes at. Will you... Stay with me? As a lover?" She asks, eyes large and full of hope.
>...Look like this city boy is staying put.

Okinawan is way more stark of a contrast compared to Kansai

Best analog I can think of is
>Tokyo Japanese = "regular" English
>Kansai Japanese = "Southern" English
>Okinawan = Cajun

You can tell that all of them have the same base, but Kansai is filled with local quirks, idioms, and turns of phrase while Okinawan is one step away from being its own language
